'''Saeki clan''' (дҪҗдјҜж°Ҹ) refers to a group of families bearing the name "Saeki" as their {{ill|Uji|ja|ж°Ҹ}} (clan name).
__TOC__{{-}}
== Overview == The Saeki clan traces its origins to {{ill|Amenootsuhiko|ja|еӨ©жҠјж—Ҙе‘Ҫ}} (Ame no Oshi-hi no Mikoto), who guided {{ill|Ninigi|ja|еҪҰзҒ«з“ҠгҖ…жқөе°Ҡ}} during the {{ill|Descent of the heavenly grandson|ja|еӨ©еӯ«йҷҚиҮЁ}}. The clan split from the {{ill|ЕҢtomo clan|ja|еӨ§дјҙж°Ҹ}} under the leadership of {{ill|ЕҢtomo no Muroya|ja|еӨ§дјҙе®ӨеұӢ}}, becoming a {{ill|Shinbetsu|ja|зҘһеҲҘ}} (descendant of deities) lineage of {{ill|Tenshin|ja|еӨ©жҙҘзҘһ}} origin. The clan name "Saeki" is believed to derive from their role in guarding the imperial court, as they were seen as those who "block (йҒ® sahe) external threats." This evolved into "Saeki" (гҒ•гҒҲгҒҚ) in modern phonetics, and in some cases as "Saiki" (гҒ•гӮҗгҒҚ).
The Saeki clan served as {{ill|Tomonomiyatsuko|ja|дјҙйҖ }}, leading the {{ill|Saeki-be|ja|дҪҗдјҜйғЁ}}, who were tasked with guarding the {{ill|Imperial Court of Japan|ja|жңқе»·}}. The gates they protected were named "Saeki Gates," though during the Heian period, under {{ill|Tang culture|ja|е”җйўЁж–ҮеҢ–}} influences, the name was changed to "Mokabe Gate" (и—»еЈҒй–Җ). Initially granted the {{ill|Kabane|ja|е§“}} of "Muraji" (йҖЈ), the Saeki clan, alongside the ЕҢtomo clan and others, was elevated to the rank of "Sukune" (е®ҝзҰ°) during the 13th year of Emperor Tenmu's reign (685 CE).
Prominent figures in the Saeki clan included {{ill|Saeki no Komaro|ja|дҪҗдјҜеӯҗйә»е‘Ӯ}}, who assisted in the assassination of Soga no Iruka, and {{ill|Saeki no Imaemaro|ja|дҪҗдјҜд»ҠжҜӣдәә}}, a statesman who served as a {{ill|Sangi|ja|еҸӮиӯ°}} and {{ill|Dazai no Sochi|ja|еӨӘе®°еёҘ}}. Military leaders such as {{ill|Saeki no Tsurugite|ja|дҪҗдјҜдё№зөҢжүӢ}}, who served under Soga no Umako, and {{ill|Saeki no Ishiyu|ja|дҪҗдјҜзҹіж№Ҝ}}, a general during campaigns against the Emishi, were also notable. However, by the end of the Heian period, the clan gradually declined from mid-level aristocracy to {{ill|Chikage|ja|ең°дёӢе®¶}} (bureaucrats of lower rank).
The Saeki name was carried on by families like the Ono family, who produced the herbalist {{ill|Ono Ranzan|ja|е°ҸйҮҺиҳӯеұұ}}, and artists such as {{ill|Kishi Ganku|ja|еІёй§’}} of the Kishi school.
== Related Lineages == ### Saeki no Miyatsuko (дҪҗдјҜйҖ ) The Saeki no Miyatsuko lineage is documented in the {{ill|Shinsen ShЕҚjiroku|ja|ж–°ж’°е§“ж°ҸйҢІ}}, appearing under the {{ill|Right Capital|ja|еҸідә¬}} Shinbetsu. They were originally known as "Saeki-be" and managed the Saeki-be labor group.
### Saeki no Obito (дҪҗдјҜйҰ–) The Saeki no Obito line appears in the Shinbetsu of {{ill|Kawachi Province|ja|жІіеҶ…еӣҪ}} as recorded in the Shinsen ShЕҚjiroku.
== Saeki-be == The Saeki-be, managed by the central Saeki clan, was a labor group organized as part of the {{ill|Shinbetsu|ja|е“ҒйғЁ}} system. Local Saeki-be groups were supervised by the {{ill|Saeki no Ason|ja|дҪҗдјҜзӣҙ}} lineage.
