Prominent figures in the Saeki clan included {{ill|Saeki no Komaro|ja|дҪҗдјҜеӯҗйә»е‘Ӯ|12=draft}}, who assisted in the assassination of Soga no Iruka, and {{ill|Saeki no Imaemaro|ja|дҪҗдјҜд»ҠжҜӣдәә|12=draft}}, a statesman who served as a {{ill|Sangi|ja|еҸӮиӯ°|12=draft}} and {{ill|Dazai no Sochi|ja|еӨӘе®°еёҘ|12=draft}}. Military leaders such as {{ill|Saeki no Tsurugite|ja|дҪҗдјҜдё№зөҢжүӢ|12=draft}}, who served under Soga no Umako, and {{ill|Saeki no Ishiyu|ja|дҪҗдјҜзҹіж№Ҝ|12=draft}}, a general during campaigns against the Emishi, were also notable. However, by the end of the Heian period, the clan gradually declined from mid-level aristocracy to {{ill|Chikage|ja|ең°дёӢе®¶|12=draft}} (bureaucrats of lower rank).







The Saeki name was carried on by families like the Ono family, who produced the herbalist {{ill|Ono Ranzan|ja|е°ҸйҮҺиҳӯеұұ|12=draft}}, and artists such as {{ill|Kishi Ganku|ja|еІёй§’|12=draft}} of the Kishi school.







== Related Lineages ==



=== Saeki no Miyatsuko (дҪҗдјҜйҖ )



The Saeki no Miyatsuko lineage is documented in the {{ill|Shinsen ShЕҚjiroku|ja|ж–°ж’°е§“ж°ҸйҢІ|1=Shinsen ShЕҚjiroku|12=draft}}, appearing under the {{ill|Right Capital|ja|еҸідә¬|12=draft}} Shinbetsu. They were originally known as "Saeki-be" and managed the Saeki-be labor group.







=== Saeki no Obito (дҪҗдјҜйҰ–)



The Saeki no Obito line appears in the Shinbetsu of {{ill|Kawachi Province|ja|жІіеҶ…еӣҪ|12=draft}} as recorded in the Shinsen ShЕҚjiroku.







== Saeki-be ==



The Saeki-be, managed by the central Saeki clan, was a labor group organized as part of the {{ill|Shinbetsu|ja|е“ҒйғЁ|12=draft}} system. Local Saeki-be groups were supervised by the {{ill|Saeki no Ason|ja|дҪҗдјҜзӣҙ|12=draft}} lineage.







