'''Saeki clan''' (дҪҗдјҜж°Ҹ) refers to a group of families bearing the name "Saeki" as their {{ill|Uji|ja|ж°Ҹ|1=Uji (clan)|lt=Uji|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Uji|13=User:Immanuelle/Uji (clan)|qq=}} (clan name).

__TOC__{{-}}

== Overview ==
The Saeki clan traces its origins to {{ill|Amenootsuhiko|ja|еӨ©жҠјж—Ҙе‘Ҫ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Amenootsuhiko|qq=}} (Ame no Oshi-hi no Mikoto), who guided {{ill|Ninigi|ja|еҪҰзҒ«з“ҠгҖ…жқөе°Ҡ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ninigi|qq=}} during the {{ill|Descent of the heavenly grandson|ja|еӨ©еӯ«йҷҚиҮЁ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Descent of the heavenly grandson|qq=}}. The clan split from the {{ill|ЕҢtomo clan|ja|еӨ§дјҙж°Ҹ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/ЕҢtomo clan|qq=}} under the leadership of {{ill|ЕҢtomo no Muroya|ja|еӨ§дјҙе®ӨеұӢ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/ЕҢtomo no Muroya|qq=}}, becoming a {{ill|Shinbetsu|ja|зҘһеҲҘ|1=Shinbetsu|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbetsu|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbetsu|qq=}} (descendant of deities) lineage of {{ill|Tenshin|ja|еӨ©жҙҘзҘһ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenshin|qq=}} origin. The clan name "Saeki" is believed to derive from their role in guarding the imperial court, as they were seen as those who "block (йҒ® sahe) external threats." This evolved into "Saeki" (гҒ•гҒҲгҒҚ) in modern phonetics, and in some cases as "Saiki" (гҒ•гӮҗгҒҚ).

The Saeki clan served as {{ill|Tomonomiyatsuko|ja|дјҙйҖ |qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tomonomiyatsuko|qq=}}, leading the {{ill|Saeki-be|ja|дҪҗдјҜйғЁ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saeki-be|qq=}}, who were tasked with guarding the {{ill|Imperial Court of Japan|ja|жңқе»·|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imperial Court of Japan|qq=}}. The gates they protected were named "Saeki Gates," though during the Heian period, under {{ill|Tang culture|ja|е”җйўЁж–ҮеҢ–|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tang culture|qq=}} influences, the name was changed to "Mokabe Gate" (и—»еЈҒй–Җ). Initially granted the {{ill|Kabane|ja|е§“|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kabane|qq=}} of "Muraji" (йҖЈ), the Saeki clan, alongside the ЕҢtomo clan and others, was elevated to the Rank of "Sukune" (е®ҝзҰ°) during the 13th year of Emperor Tenmu's reign (685 CE).

Prominent figures in the Saeki clan included {{ill|Saeki no Komaro|ja|дҪҗдјҜеӯҗйә»е‘Ӯ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saeki no Komaro|qq=}}, who assisted in the assassination of Soga no Iruka, and {{ill|Saeki no Imaemaro|ja|дҪҗдјҜд»ҠжҜӣдәә|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saeki no Imaemaro|qq=}}, a statesman who served as a {{ill|Sangi|ja|еҸӮиӯ°|1=Sangi (Japan)|lt=Sangi|2=ja|3=еҸӮиӯ°|4=ru|5=РЎР°РҪРіРё|6=fr|7=Sangi_(Japon)|8=ko|9=м°ёмқҳ_(мқјліёмӮ¬)|10=es|11=Sangi|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sangi|qq=}} and {{ill|Dazai no Sochi|ja|еӨӘе®°еёҘ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Dazai no Sochi|qq=}}. Military leaders such as {{ill|Saeki no Tsurugite|ja|дҪҗдјҜдё№зөҢжүӢ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saeki no Tsurugite|qq=}}, who served under Soga no Umako, and {{ill|Saeki no Ishiyu|ja|дҪҗдјҜзҹіж№Ҝ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saeki no Ishiyu|qq=}}, a general during campaigns against the Emishi, were also notable. However, by the end of the Heian period, the clan gradually declined from mid-level aristocracy to {{ill|Chikage|ja|ең°дёӢе®¶|1=Jigeke|2=ja|3=ең°дёӢе®¶|lt=Jigeke|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chikage|13=User:Immanuelle/Jigeke|qq=}} (bureaucrats of lower Rank).

The Saeki name was carried on by families like the Ono family, who produced the herbalist {{ill|Ono Ranzan|ja|е°ҸйҮҺиҳӯеұұ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ono Ranzan|qq=}}, and artists such as {{ill|Kishi Ganku|ja|еІёй§’|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kishi Ganku|qq=}} of the Kishi school.

== Related Lineages ==
=== Saeki no Miyatsuko (дҪҗдјҜйҖ )
The Saeki no Miyatsuko lineage is documented in the {{ill|Shinsen ShЕҚjiroku|ja|ж–°ж’°е§“ж°ҸйҢІ|1=Shinsen ShЕҚjiroku|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinsen ShЕҚjiroku|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinsen ShЕҚjiroku|qq=}}, appearing under the {{ill|Right Capital|ja|еҸідә¬|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Right Capital|qq=}} Shinbetsu. They were originally known as "Saeki-be" and managed the Saeki-be labor group.

=== Saeki no Obito (дҪҗдјҜйҰ–)
The Saeki no Obito line appears in the Shinbetsu of {{ill|Kawachi Province|ja|жІіеҶ…еӣҪ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kawachi Province|qq=}} as recorded in the Shinsen ShЕҚjiroku.

== Saeki-be ==
The Saeki-be, managed by the central Saeki clan, was a labor group organized as part of the {{ill|Shinbetsu|ja|е“ҒйғЁ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbetsu|qq=}} system. Local Saeki-be groups were supervised by the {{ill|Saeki no Ason|ja|дҪҗдјҜзӣҙ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saeki no Ason|qq=}} lineage.

