'''Saeki clan''' (дҪҗдјҜж°Ҹ) refers to a group of families bearing the name "Saeki" as their [[:en:Uji (clan)|Uji]] (clan name).

__TOC__{{-}}

== Overview ==
The Saeki clan traces its origins to {{ill|Amenootsuhiko|ja|еӨ©жҠјж—Ҙе‘Ҫ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Amenootsuhiko|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to гӮўгғЎгғҺгӮӘгӮ·гғ’|1=AmanЕҚshihi|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q10939616}} (Ame no Oshi-hi no Mikoto), who guided {{ill|Ninigi-no-Mikoto|lt=Ninigi-no-Mikoto|lt=Ninigi|ja|еҪҰзҒ«з“ҠгҖ…жқөе°Ҡ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ninigi|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to гғӢгғӢгӮ®}} during the [[:en:Tenson kЕҚrin|Descent of the heavenly grandson]]. The clan split from the [[:en:ЕҢtomo clan (ancient)|ЕҢtomo clan]] under the leadership of {{ill|ЕҢtomo no Muroya|ja|еӨ§дјҙе®ӨеұӢ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/ЕҢtomo no Muroya|qq=|1=Muroya Ootomo|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11432336}}, becoming a {{ill|Shinbetsu|ja|зҘһеҲҘ|1=Shinbetsu|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbetsu|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbetsu|qq=}} (descendant of deities) lineage of {{ill|Tenshin|ja|еӨ©жҙҘзҘһ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenshin|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to еӨ©жҙҘзҘһгғ»еӣҪжҙҘзҘһ|1=Amatsukami and Kunitsukami|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11442793}} origin. The clan name "Saeki" is believed to derive from their role in guarding the imperial court, as they were seen as those who "block (йҒ® sahe) external threats." This evolved into "Saeki" (гҒ•гҒҲгҒҚ) in modern phonetics, and in some cases as "Saiki" (гҒ•гӮҗгҒҚ).

The Saeki clan served as {{ill|Tomonomiyatsuko|ja|дјҙйҖ |qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tomonomiyatsuko|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}}, leading the [[:en:Saeki people|Saeki-be]], who were tasked with guarding the [[:en:Royal court|Imperial Court of Japan]]. The gates they protected were named "Saeki Gates," though during the Heian period, under {{ill|Tang culture|ja|е”җйўЁж–ҮеҢ–|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tang culture|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to еӨ©е№іж–ҮеҢ–|1=TenpyЕҚ culture|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q5525117}} influences, the name was changed to "Mokabe Gate" (и—»еЈҒй–Җ). Initially granted the {{ill|Kabane|ja|е§“|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kabane|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}} of "Muraji" (йҖЈ), the Saeki clan, alongside the ЕҢtomo clan and others, was elevated to the Rank of "Sukune" (е®ҝзҰ°) during the 13th year of Emperor Tenmu's reign (685 CE).

Prominent figures in the Saeki clan included {{ill|Saeki no Komaro|ja|дҪҗдјҜеӯҗйә»е‘Ӯ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saeki no Komaro|qq=|1=Saeki no Komaro|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11382809}}, who assisted in the assassination of Soga no Iruka, and {{ill|Saeki no Imaemaro|ja|дҪҗдјҜд»ҠжҜӣдәә|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saeki no Imaemaro|qq=|1=Saeki no Imaemishi|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11382787}}, a statesman who served as a [[:en:Sangi (Japan)|Sangi]] and {{ill|Dazai no Sochi|ja|еӨӘе®°еёҘ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Dazai no Sochi|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to еӨ§е®°еёҘ}}. Military leaders such as {{ill|Saeki no Tsurugite|ja|дҪҗдјҜдё№зөҢжүӢ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saeki no Tsurugite|qq=|1=Saeki no Nifute|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q45828498}}, who served under Soga no Umako, and {{ill|Saeki no Ishiyu|ja|дҪҗдјҜзҹіж№Ҝ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saeki no Ishiyu|qq=|1=Saeki no Iwayu|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11382879}}, a general during campaigns against the Emishi, were also notable. However, by the end of the Heian period, the clan gradually declined from mid-level aristocracy to {{ill|Chikage|ja|ең°дёӢе®¶|1=Jigeke|2=ja|3=ең°дёӢе®¶|lt=Jigeke|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chikage|13=User:Immanuelle/Jigeke|qq=|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11424052}} (bureaucrats of lower Rank).

The Saeki name was carried on by families like the Ono family, who produced the herbalist [[:en:Ono Ranzan|Ono Ranzan]], and artists such as [[:en:Kishi Ganku|Kishi Ganku]] of the Kishi school.

== Related Lineages ==
=== Saeki no Miyatsuko (дҪҗдјҜйҖ )
The Saeki no Miyatsuko lineage is documented in the [[:en:Shinsen ShЕҚjiroku|Shinsen ShЕҚjiroku]], appearing under the [[:en:Ukyo|Right Capital]] Shinbetsu. They were originally known as "Saeki-be" and managed the Saeki-be labor group.

=== Saeki no Obito (дҪҗдјҜйҰ–)
The Saeki no Obito line appears in the Shinbetsu of [[:en:Kawachi Province|Kawachi Province]] as recorded in the Shinsen ShЕҚjiroku.

== Saeki-be ==
The Saeki-be, managed by the central Saeki clan, was a labor group organized as part of the [[:en:Shinabe clans|Shinbetsu]] system. Local Saeki-be groups were supervised by the {{ill|Saeki no Ason|ja|дҪҗдјҜзӣҙ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saeki no Ason|qq=|1=Nao Saeki|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11382874}} lineage.

